clauses.body_md:
9.1 **Location of Processing**: The Processor shall process Personal Data in {{processing_location}}.

{{#if international_transfers}}
9.2 **Transfers Outside the UK**: Where Personal Data subject to UK GDPR is transferred to, or processed in, a country outside the UK that has not been recognised by the UK Secretary of State as providing adequate protection under section 17A of the Data Protection Act 2018:

   (a) the parties shall implement appropriate safeguards as required by Chapter V of the UK GDPR, including:

      (i) entering into the International Data Transfer Addendum (IDTA) to the EU Commission Standard Contractual Clauses, which is hereby incorporated by reference; or

      (ii) relying on other valid transfer mechanisms under Article 46 UK GDPR (e.g., binding corporate rules, approved codes of conduct, approved certification mechanisms);

   (b) for the purposes of the IDTA:

      (i) the Controller is the "data exporter" and the Processor is the "data importer";

      (ii) Tables 1-3 of the IDTA are completed as set out in Schedule 1 (Processing Details) and Schedule 3 (Sub-processors) of this DPA;

      (iii) the parties shall comply with the IDTA and the EU SCCs (as modified by the IDTA) as applicable to the relationship between controller and processor;

   (c) the Processor shall implement appropriate supplementary measures (technical, organisational, and contractual) to ensure an essentially equivalent level of protection as guaranteed by UK GDPR, taking into account:

      (i) the circumstances of the transfer;

      (ii) the laws and practices of the destination country, including requirements for public authorities to access Personal Data (conducting a "Transfer Risk Assessment" as recommended by the ICO);

      (iii) the Security Measures applied; and

      (iv) guidance from the ICO and the European Data Protection Board (EDPB);

   (d) the Processor shall provide the Controller with all information reasonably necessary to assess the adequacy of supplementary measures and compliance with UK Data Protection Legislation in relation to international transfers;

   (e) the Processor shall promptly notify the Controller if:

      (i) it receives a request from a public authority or government body for access to Personal Data, except where otherwise prohibited by law (such as a prohibition under criminal law to preserve the confidentiality of a law enforcement investigation);

      (ii) it becomes aware of any changes in the laws or practices of the destination country that may affect the level of protection afforded to Personal Data; or

      (iii) it is unable to comply with its obligations under the IDTA or SCCs.

9.3 **UK Adequacy Bridge**: Where the destination country has received an adequacy decision from the UK Secretary of State under section 17A of the Data Protection Act 2018, transfers may proceed on that basis without the need for additional safeguards, provided the adequacy decision remains valid.

9.4 **Dual Compliance**: Where this DPA governs Personal Data subject to both UK GDPR and EU GDPR:

   (a) both the IDTA (for UK transfers) and the EU SCCs (for EU transfers) shall apply as appropriate;

   (b) the Processor shall comply with the more stringent requirement where the two regimes differ; and

   (c) the Processor shall maintain records sufficient to demonstrate compliance with both regimes.
{{/if}}

{{^if international_transfers}}
9.2 **No International Transfers**: The Processor warrants that Personal Data shall not be transferred to, or processed in, any country outside the UK without the Controller's prior written consent and without implementing appropriate safeguards as required by Chapter V of the UK GDPR.
{{/if}}

9.5 **Onward Transfers**: Where a Sub-processor located outside the UK will process Personal Data, the requirements of this Clause 9 shall apply to such onward transfers, and the Processor shall ensure that the Sub-processor enters into appropriate transfer agreements (IDTA or equivalent).
